array.notes: This punctuation mark looks like an upwards-poiting triangle of dots with a comma between (and below) the two lower dots. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301 and 307. See also 2234 above in Mathematical Operators.

array.description: PUNCTUS EXCLAMATIVUS
array.notes: Early form with two dots below each other and a diagonal stroke on top of them. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, p. 301.

array.description: PUNCTUS INTERROGATIVUS HORIZONTAL TILDE
array.notes: This is a variant of the question mark where the swash (tilde) is horizontal. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, p. 301.

array.description: PUNCTUS VERSUS
array.notes: Similar in shape to the semicolon (003B), but should be kept apart from this mark. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301, 306.

array.description: SIGNE DE RENVOI
array.notes: Looks like two dots over a single dot. Used to connect a marginal note to a place in the text. Looks similar to TWO DOTS OVER ONE DOT PUNCTUATION below, but has a different usage and the dots are more widely spaced.

array.description: PUNCTUS ELEVATUS DIAGONAL STROKE
array.notes: Variant form of the punctus elevatus.

array.description: PUNCTUS INTERROGATIVUS LEMNISKATE FORM
array.notes: Attested in Old Icelandic, but very marginal. For examples, see Holm perg 15 B 4to (cf. Hreinn Benediktsson, Early Icelandic Script, Reykjav\u00edk 1965, pl. 8:13 and 8:19).

array.description: TWO DOTS OVER COMMA POSITURA
array.notes: Attested in Old Icelandic, e.g. in Holm perg 15 B 4to (see Hreinn Benediktsson, Early Icelandic Script, Reykjav\u00edk 1965, pl. 8:14) and in GKS 2365 4to (Codex Regius of the Eddic poems).

array.description: VIRGULA SUSPENSIVA
array.notes: Looks like a solidus with a dot in the middle. Used to mark a very brief pause or hesitation in the text. Cf. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, p. 307.

array.description: PUNCTUS FLEXUS
array.notes: Looks like the digit 7 with a dot below, sometimes referred to as \u2018seven and point\u2019 (e.g. by N.R. Ker, English Manuscripts in the Century after the Norman Conquest, Oxford, 1960, p. 47). Also called PUNCTUS CIRCUMFLEXUS. Used to mark sentence-medial pauses, especially in liturgical texts where the pitch of the voice drops. Cf. also Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, pp. 301, 306. Note that the shape in Parkes\u2019 book looks more like an open \u2018a\u2019 than \u20187\u2019, but this is basically a question of variance.

array.description: SHORT VIRGULA
array.notes: Looks like a virgule, but confined within the \u2018x\u2019 height (like a half-height slash), e.g. \u2018x \uf1f7 x\u2019. Attested in late paper manuscripts of Medieval Nordic verse and not to be unified with the ordinary comma.

array.description: DISTINCTIO
array.notes: Described by the grammarian Donatus, who distinguishes between three positions of the dot: on the baseline (to be unified with 002E FULL STOP), middle height (to be unified with 00B7 MIDDLE DOT) and the high dot, shown here. See also Isidore of Sevilla, Etymologiae I 20. Malcolm B. Parkes, Pause and Effect, Aldershot, 1992, p. 13, says that the distinctio was used to indicate \u201ca final pause, after a periodus, or where the sententia is completed\u201d.

array.description: WAVY LINE
array.notes: Frequently used in English manuscripts in the 12th century in the form of a wavy line or sometimes a straight line. Placed slightly above the base line.

array.description: PUNCTUS ELEVATUS WITH HIGH BACK
array.notes: Variant form of the punctus elevatus found in manuscripts in the Low countries, eastern France and the Rhineland.

array.description: PUNCTUS ELEVATUS WITH ONSET
array.notes: Variant form of the punctus elevatus found in manuscripts from southern Germany.

array.description: COMBINING TRIPLE BREVE BELOW
array.notes: Used below character sequences like \u2018sch\u2019 in the \u201cRheinische Dokumenta\u201d, a semi-official phonetic notation of Low German dialects.
